          <msContents>
            <summary><p>Bifolium on parchment; Shelfmark: HC.MS.03172; Qurʾānic Text:  Q 101:9-102:5; Lines per page: 5; Dimensions: 209-214 x 158-164 mm; Script  style: Large Maġribī <hi rend="italic">mabsūṭ</hi>, angular chrysography; Estimated  date of production: 13th or early 14th century; Provenance: Northwest  Africa (Maġrib) or Muslim Iberia (al-Andalus).</p><p> </p><p>  </p><p>This kind of perforations on each page, forming the word <hi rend="italic">ḥabs </hi>(the Maġribī equivalent of <hi rend="italic">waqf</hi>), was an endowment practice attested under the Marinids between the 1290s and the 1330s. The manuscript must therefore be earlier. Yellow/orange dots mark the <hi rend="italic">hamza </hi>above or below <hi rend="italic">alif</hi>, and green dots signal <hi rend="italic">alif al-waṣl</hi>. The symbols of <hi rend="italic">sukūn </hi>and <hi rend="italic">tašdīd </hi>are traced in blue, in contrast with all the other vocalisation marks, which are in red. A similar manuscript in vertical format, featuring 5 lines per page, and perforated with the word <hi rend="italic">ḥabs </hi>is in London, British Library, ms. Or. 11780.</p><p> </p>Image no. 1 shows one page, image no. 2 shows the bifolium. Originally, fragments <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/101/vers/9?handschrift=1415">HC.MS.03149</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/89/vers/11?handschrift=1399">HC.MS.03173</ref> and HC.MS.03172 are frome the same manuscript.
                    </summary>
